			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>Graphical Template Language for Transformation Synthesis</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ElīnaKalniņa.html">Elīna Kalniņa</a>, <a href="../profile/AudrisKalniņš.html">Audris Kalniņš</a>, <a href="../profile/EdgarsCelms.html">Edgars Celms</a>, <a href="../profile/AgrisŠostaks.html">Agris Šostaks</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_18">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_18</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagM">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> It proposes a template language aimed at synthesizing model transformations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> The language is graphical, making visualization/graphical notation central to its approach.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Transformation synthesis ultimately produces mappings between source and target models.
</li></ul></li></ul>
